{{Unreferenced|date=November 2006}}
A '''mesonic molecule''' is a set of two or more [[meson]]s bound together by the [[strong force]]. Unlike [[atomic nucleus|baryonic molecules]], which form the nuclei of all elements in nature save [[Hydrogen atom|hydrogen-1]], a mesonic molecule has yet to be definitively observed. The [[X(3872)]] discovered in 2003 and the [[Z(4430)]] discovered in 2007 by the [[Belle experiment]] are the best candidates for such an observation.

